<div class="row">
 <div align="center" class="col-xs-12"><h4><b>Thithi</b></h4></div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->

<!-- Solar Calendar ::: Start  -->
<div class="row" style="line-height:24px;">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div><h5><b>Solar Calendar</b></h5></div>
 <div>
  Sun moves by 360<sup>0</sup> in a year (Solar Year) and 30<sup>0</sup> in a month (Solar Month).
  Each Solar month consists of 30 days (Sun moves exactly 1<sup>0</sup>) in a day.
 </div>
 <div class="list-group">
 <div class="list-group-item">
  This calendar will be used in dasas and in Tajaka analysis.
 </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
 </div><!--/.list-group -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Solar Calendar ::: End  -->
<!-- Lunar Calendar ::: Start  -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div align="center"><h5><b>Lunar Calendar</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div><h5><b>Lunar Day</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div>
  A lunar month consists of 30 tithis. One day stands for one tithi. 
  Tithi is a period in which the difference between the longitudes of Moon and Sun changes by exactly 12<sup>0</sup>.
  Each month is divided into two 
  <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Two weeks">fortnights</code> (pakshas).<br/>
  During Sukla/Suddha paksha,
  <ul>
   <li>Moon is waxing.</li>
   <li>Moon is ahead of Sun by an amount that is between 0<sup>0</sup> and 180<sup>0</sup></li>
  </ul>
  During Krishna/Bahula paksha,
  <ul>
   <li>Moon is waning.</li>
   <li>Moon is ahead of Sun by an amount that is between 180<sup>0</sup> and 360<sup>0</sup></li>
  </ul>
  At the end of a month, Sun-Moon longitude differential will be 360<sup>0</sup>.
  It means that Moon will finish one cycle around the zodiac and catch up with Sun
  again. So Sun and Moon will be at the same longitude again. Then a new month starts.
 </div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
 <div class="list-group">
 <div class="list-group-item">
  <div><b>Procedure to Find Thithi of a day using Sun's Longitude and Moon's Longitude:</b></div>
  <div>
    <ol>
	  <li><b>Find the Difference: </b>(Moon’s longitude – Sun’s longitude)</li>
	  <li>If above result is Negative, add 360<sup>0</sup>, then the result will be between 0<sup>0</sup> and 360<sup>0</sup>.</li>
	  <li>Divide the result by 12<sup>0</sup>.Ignore the remainder and take the quotient.</li>
	  <li>Add 1 to the quotient. You get a number from 1 to 30. That will give the index of the tithi running.</li>
	</ol>
  </div>
 </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
 </div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row mtop15p">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <div><h5><b>Lunar Months</b></h5></div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 When Sun and Moon are at the same longitude, New Lunar Month begins.<br/>
 The name of a lunar month is decided by the rasi in which Sun-Moon 
 <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Two planets are said to be in conjunction, if they are exactly at the same longitude">conjunction</code> takes place.
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
 <div align="center"><h5><b>Adhika Maasa</b></h5></div>
 <div><b>Solar year -</b> 365.2425 days (12 months)</div>
 <div><b>Lunar year -</b> 355 days (12 months)</div>
 <div>
  Once in every three years, an extra month comes (covering 10 days in each year into a month in 3rd year).
  That month is called as <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="Sanskrit word: Extra Month">Adhika Maasa</code>
 </div>
 <div>
  <h5 align="center"><b>When this Adhika Maasa occurs in the 3rd year?</b></h5>
  When Sun-Moon conjunction occurs twice in a rasi. Then, the month associated with that raasi occurs 
  for two times. One is called as Nija XXXXX Maasa and other is called as Adhika XXXXX Maasa.
  <div>
   <b>Example:</b><br/>
   Lets consider Sun-Moon conjunction occurs twice in Taurus Raasi. Then, One is called as <i>Nija Jyeshtha Maasa</i> and 
   other is called as <i>Adhika Jyeshtha Maasa</i>.
  </div>
 </div>
</div><!--/.list-group-item -->
</div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Lunar Calendar ::: End  -->
<!-- Yoga ::: Start -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
 <h5><b>Yogas</b></h5>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
Yoga helps one to keep deep <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="pain/harm">afflictions</code> away.
There are 27 Yogas in 360 degrees.
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
 <div>
   <h5 align="center"><b>Find the Yoga of the Day</b></h5>
   <ol>
    <li><b>Find the Sum:</b> Add the longitudes of Sun and Moon.</li>
	<li>Divide the result by the length of one Nakshatra (13<sup>0</sup> 20' or 800')
	    <div class="list-group">
		  <div class="list-group-item">
			<div><b>Converting degrees into Minutes:</b></div>
			<div><b>13<sup>0</sup> 20'</b> = (13 * 60)' + 20' = 780' + 20' = <b>800'</b></div>
	      </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
		</div><!--/.list-group -->
	</li>
	<li>Ignore fractions and take the integer part</li>
	<li>Add 1 to it and the result is the index of the yoga running.</li>
   <ol>
 </div>
</div><!--/.list-group-item -->
</div><!--/.list-group -->
<!-- -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<!-- Yoga ::: End -->
<!-- Karanas ::: Start -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12"><h5><b>Karanas</b></h5></div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-12">
Each thithi is divided into 2 karanas. In a Thithi, karanas is a period in which the difference between the longitudes 
of Moon and Sun changes by exactly 6<sup>0</sup>. There are 11 Karanas:
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
<ol>
<li>
 <div><b>Bava Karana</b></div>
 <div>
   Individuals born in Bav Karana in Astrology are spiritual and like to be involved in holy activities. 
   They are divuthful and have faith in giving their best to any work that’s given to them.
 </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Balava Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    Like the earlier Karana, Baalav Karana also gives a spiritual nature to the person. People born 
	in Balav Karana may do pilgrimage and spend more time of their life doing spiritual activities.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Kaulava Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    A person born in the Kaulav Karana is very friendly. This Karana gives its people some of the 
	best talents like love and caring.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Taitula Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    Persons born in Taitula Karana are very lucky. They have a wealthy life and become a possessor 
	of buildings and properties. Love has an important role in their life and maybe this is the reason 
	they diveat people open-mindedly.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Garija Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    As per Astrology, people of Garija Karana are punctilious. They divust in their aptitude not fortune. 
	They attain their desired objective by hard work and effort.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Vanija Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    People of Vanij Karana are bright and smart. It is seen that they have an extreme interest in business 
	and take this talent for earning funds.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Vishti / Bhadra Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    As per Astrology, the Vishti Karana is not considered fortunate. This Karana cast its negative nature about 
	the person due to which the native might have a distrustful character. They may involve in immoral deeds. 
	Vishti Karan is also known as ‘Bhadrā’ Karan, and is avoided in all auspicious activities. However, 
	Vishti /Bhadra Karana is appropriate for destructive activities e.g. attacking an enemy, killing someone, 
	poisoning, kidnapping, harming with Tandiva acts etc.
  </div>
</li>
</ol>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
<div class="col-xs-6">
<ol start="8">
<li>
  <div><b>Sakuna / Shakuni Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    People of Sakuna / Shakuni Karana are the admirers of law and justice. They are very practical in solving conflicts. 
	That means they can be very capable in terminating a quarrel with their cleverness.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Chatushpada Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    Chatushpad Karana imparts spiritual feelings to its natives. Individuals born in Chatushpad Karana respect 
	educated people and help animals. They are generally very fancier of animals and know how to diveat pets 
	with medicine. They can become successful animal doctors.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Naga Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    According to Astrology, Naga Karana is a portentous one. People born in Nag Karana may be have unlucky events. 
	Their life may be full of sdivuggles and problems. They will get results only through hard work and 
	determination, and not through good fortune. Natives of Nag Karan are usually very irritated.
  </div>
</li>
<li>
  <div><b>Kimstughna Karana</b></div>
  <div>
    People of Kimstughna Karana are very lucky. They violently pursue charitable work. They will get every type of 
	contentment in their life. They also get quality education and lead a wealthy life.
  </div>
</li>
</ol>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
